{"title_page": "Svenja Adolphs", "text_new": "{{short description|British linguist|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n'''Svenja Adolphs''' is a British [[linguist]] whose research involves analysis of corpus data including sources of multimodal material such as the Nottingham Multimodal Corpus (NMMC) to examine communication in new forms of digital records. Using visual mark-up systems, her work allows a better understanding of the nature of natural language use. She is a co-founder (along with [[Paul Crawford (academic)|Paul Crawford]] and [[Ronald Carter (linguist)|Ronald Carter]]) of the Health Language Research Group at the University of Nottingham, bringing together academics and clinicians to advance the work of applied linguistics in health care settings.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://ssarangi.com/bios.htm|title = Welcome to COMET Society|date = |accessdate = 2 January 2016|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nAdolphs earned her PhD in 2001 from the [[University of Nottingham]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?did=1&uin=uk.bl.ethos.391412|title = British Library EThOS|date = |accessdate = 2 January 2016|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>  She is currently Professor of English Language and Linguistics at Nottingham and Head of the [https://www.nottingham.ac.uk/english/ School of English]. At Nottingham she has served as Director of Research (Associate Pro-Vice Chancellor) of the Faculty of Arts, Head of English Language and Applied Linguistics, Chair of the Faculty of Arts Impact Strategy Group and Chair of the Creative Industries Task Force.\n\nFrom 2004-2007 she was a member of the executive committee<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.baal.org.uk/committee/exec_mins_07_04_27.pdf|title = BAAL Executive Committee|date = |accessdate = 2 January 2016|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> of the [[British Association for Applied Linguistics]], and represented BAAL in the Network of European Applied Linguists and the International Association for Applied Linguistics.\n\nAdolphs is Principal Investigator on a grant from the [[Economic and Social Research Council]] (ESRC) that looked at adolescent language use in discussing health issues in the online forums of the Teenage Health Freak website.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk/projects?ref=ES/G036578/1|title = Gateway to Research|date = |accessdate = 2 January 2016|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> She is also Principal Investigator on an [[Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council]] (EPSRC) investigating Second Language Speech Fluency.\n\nShe is the member of a number of academic journal editorial boards, including those for ''Corpora,<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.euppublishing.com/page/cor/editorialBoard|title = Editorial Board--Edinburgh University Press|date = |accessdate = January 2, 2016|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>'' ''The International Journal of Corpus Linguistics,''<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://benjamins.com/?embed=1#catalog/journals/ijcl/board|title = John Benjamins Publishing Company|date = |accessdate = 2 January 2016|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> and the ''ELR Journal.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://ejournals.org.uk/ELR/board|title = ELR Journal--Editorial Board|date = |accessdate = January 2, 2016|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>''\n\nFrom 2014-2018 Adolphs was a member of Council, the [[Arts and Humanities Research Council]] (AHRC),<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.ahrc.ac.uk/about/visionstrategygovernance/governancestructure|title = Governance Structure|date = |accessdate = 2 January 2016|website = Arts and Humanities Research Council|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> governing body responsible for the overall strategic direction of the AHRC, including its key objectives and targets. This is a position which was appointed by the Minister for Universities and Science. She is also a member of the Strategic Advisory Network of the [[Economic and Social Research Council|ESRC]].\n\nOn 12 October 2017 she became a [[Fellow of the Academy of Social Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Sixty-nine leading social scientists conferred as Fellows of the Academy of Social Sciences {{!}} |url=https://www.acss.org.uk/news/sixty-nine-leading-social-scientists-conferred-fellows-academy-social-sciences/ |website=www.acss.org.uk |accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Selected publications ==\n\nS. Adolphs and R.Carter. 2013. ''Spoken corpus linguistics: from monomodal to multimodal.'' Routledge.\n\nS. Adolphs. 2008. ''Corpus and context: Investigating pragmatic functions in spoken discourse.'' John Benjamins.\n\nS Adolphs. 2006. ''Introducing electronic text analysis: A practical guide for language and literary studies.'' Routledge.\n\nS. Adolphs, B. Brown, R. Carter, P. Crawford, and O. Sahota. 2004. \"Applying corpus linguistics in a health care context,\" ''Journal of Applied Linguistics and Professional Practice.''\n\nN. Schmitt, Z. Dornyei, S. Adolphs, and V. Durow. 2004. \"Knowledge and acquisition of formulaic sequences,\" ''Formulaic Sequences: Acquisition, Processing, and Use.'' John Benjamins.\n\nS. Adolphs and N. Schmitt. 2003. \"Lexical coverage of spoken discourse,\" ''Applied Linguistics.''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nottingham.ac.uk/english/people/svenja.adolphs Faculty page]\n* {{twitter|svenjauk}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adolphs, Svenja}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Linguists from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Women linguists]]\n[[Category:British women writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Nottingham]]\n[[Category:21st-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Academy of Social Sciences]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British linguist|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n'''Svenja Adolphs''' is a British [[linguist]] whose research involves analysis of corpus data including sources of multimodal material such as the Nottingham Multimodal Corpus (NMMC) to examine communication in new forms of digital records. Using visual mark-up systems, her work allows a better understanding of the nature of natural language use. She is a co-founder (along with [[Paul Crawford (academic)|Paul Crawford]] and [[Ronald Carter (linguist)|Ronald Carter]]) of the Health Language Research Group at the University of Nottingham, bringing together academics and clinicians to advance the work of applied linguistics in health care settings.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://ssarangi.com/bios.htm|title = Welcome to COMET Society|date = |accessdate = 2 January 2016|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nAdolphs earned her PhD in 2001 from the [[University of Nottingham]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?did=1&uin=uk.bl.ethos.391412|title = British Library EThOS|date = |accessdate = 2 January 2016|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>  She is currently Professor of English Language and Linguistics at Nottingham and Head of the [https://www.nottingham.ac.uk/english/ School of English]. At Nottingham she has served as Director of Research (Associate Pro-Vice Chancellor) of the Faculty of Arts, Head of English Language and Applied Linguistics, Chair of the Faculty of Arts Impact Strategy Group and Chair of the Creative Industries Task Force.\n\nFrom 2004-2007 she was a member of the executive committee<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.baal.org.uk/committee/exec_mins_07_04_27.pdf|title = BAAL Executive Committee|date = |accessdate = 2 January 2016|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> of the [[British Association for Applied Linguistics]], and represented BAAL in the Network of European Applied Linguists and the International Association for Applied Linguistics.\n\nAdolphs is Principal Investigator on a grant from the [[Economic and Social Research Council]] (ESRC) that looked at adolescent language use in discussing health issues in the online forums of the Teenage Health Freak website.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk/projects?ref=ES/G036578/1|title = Gateway to Research|date = |accessdate = 2 January 2016|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> She is also Principal Investigator on an [[Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council]] (EPSRC) investigating Second Language Speech Fluency.\n\nShe is the member of a number of academic journal editorial boards, including those for ''Corpora,<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.euppublishing.com/page/cor/editorialBoard|title = Editorial Board--Edinburgh University Press|date = |accessdate = January 2, 2016|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>'' ''The International Journal of Corpus Linguistics,''<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://benjamins.com/?embed=1#catalog/journals/ijcl/board|title = John Benjamins Publishing Company|date = |accessdate = 2 January 2016|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> and the ''ELR Journal.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://ejournals.org.uk/ELR/board|title = ELR Journal--Editorial Board|date = |accessdate = January 2, 2016|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>''\n\nFrom 2014-2018 Adolphs was a member of Council, the [[Arts and Humanities Research Council]] (AHRC),<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.ahrc.ac.uk/about/visionstrategygovernance/governancestructure|title = Governance Structure|date = |accessdate = 2 January 2016|website = Arts and Humanities Research Council|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> governing body responsible for the overall strategic direction of the AHRC, including its key objectives and targets. This is a position which was appointed by the Minister for Universities and Science. She is also a member of the Strategic Advisory Network of the [[Economic and Social Research Council|ESRC]].\n\nOn 12 October 2017 she became a [[Fellow of the Academy of Social Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Sixty-nine leading social scientists conferred as Fellows of the Academy of Social Sciences {{!}} |url=https://www.acss.org.uk/news/sixty-nine-leading-social-scientists-conferred-fellows-academy-social-sciences/ |website=www.acss.org.uk |accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Selected publications ==\n\nS. Adolphs and R.Carter. 2013. ''Spoken corpus linguistics: from monomodal to multimodal.'' Routledge.\n\nS. Adolphs. 2008. ''Corpus and context: Investigating pragmatic functions in spoken discourse.'' John Benjamins.\n\nS Adolphs. 2006. ''Introducing electronic text analysis: A practical guide for language and literary studies.'' Routledge.\n\nS. Adolphs, B. Brown, R. Carter, P. Crawford, and O. Sahota. 2004. \"Applying corpus linguistics in a health care context,\" ''Journal of Applied Linguistics and Professional Practice.''\n\nN. Schmitt, Z. Dornyei, S. Adolphs, and V. Durow. 2004. \"Knowledge and acquisition of formulaic sequences,\" ''Formulaic Sequences: Acquisition, Processing, and Use.'' John Benjamins.\n\nS. Adolphs and N. Schmitt. 2003. \"Lexical coverage of spoken discourse,\" ''Applied Linguistics.''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nottingham.ac.uk/english/people/svenja.adolphs Faculty page]\n* [https://twitter.com/svenjauk Twitter page]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adolphs, Svenja}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Linguists from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Women linguists]]\n[[Category:British women writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Nottingham]]\n[[Category:21st-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Academy of Social Sciences]]\n", "name_user":