publisher=Elsevier |place=Oxford |doi=10.1016/B0-08-044854-2/02265-3}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Picard|first=Marc |year=1984 |title=On the Naturalness of Algonquian {{IPA|\u026c}} |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=50 |issue=4 |pages=424\u2013437 |jstor=1265401 |doi=10.1086/465851}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Proulx|first=Paul |year=1977 |title=Connective Vowels in Proto-Algonquian |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=43 |issue=2 |pages=156\u2013157 |jstor=1264935 |doi=10.1086/465473}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Proulx|first=Paul |year=1980 |title=The Subordinative Order of Proto-Algonquian |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=46 |issue=4 |pages=289\u2013300 |jstor=1264710 |doi=10.1086/465664}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Proulx|first=Paul |year=1982 |title=The Origin of the Absolute Verbs of the Algonquian Independent Order |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=48 |issue=4 |pages=394\u2013411 |jstor=1264842 |doi=10.1086/465749}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Proulx|first=Paul |year=1984a |title=Proto-Algic I: Phonological Sketch |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=50 |issue=2 |pages=165\u2013207 |jstor=1265603 |doi=10.1086/465826}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Proulx|first=Paul |year=1984b |title=Algonquian Objective Verbs |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=50 |issue=4 |pages=403\u2013423 |jstor=1265400 |doi=10.1086/465850}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Proulx|first=Paul |year=1989 |title=A Sketch of Blackfoot Historical Phonology |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=55 |issue=1 |pages=43\u201382 |jstor=1265411 |doi=10.1086/466104}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Siebert Jr.|first=Frank T. |title=Certain Proto-Algonquian Consonant Clusters |journal=Language |year=1941 |volume=17 |issue=4 |pages=298\u2013303 |doi=10.2307/409280 |jstor=409280 |publisher=Linguistic Society of America}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Siebert Jr.|first=Frank T. |title=Contributions to Anthropology: Linguistics I (Algonquian) |contribution=The Original Home of the Proto-Algonquian People |publisher=National Museum of Canada, Bulletin 214 |year=1967 |place=Ottawa |series=Anthropological Series 78 |pages=13\u201347 |oclc=102526}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Teeter|first=Karl V. |authorlink=Karl V. Teeter |year=1965 |title=The Algonquian Verb: Notes Toward a Reconsideration |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=31 |issue=3 |pages=221\u2013225 |jstor=1263896 |doi=10.1086/464840}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Thomason|first=Lucy |contribution=Proto-Algonkian Phonology and Morpho-Syntax |title=Encyclopedia of Language & Linguistics |edition=2nd |volume=10 |pages=190\u2013198 |year=2006 |publisher=Elsevier |place=Oxford |doi=10.1016/B0-08-044854-2/01896-4}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Weggelaar, C. |year=1974 |title=The Algonquian Verb: Another Reconsideration |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=40 |issue=3 |pages=249\u2013253 |jstor=1264864 |doi=10.1086/465316}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://protoalgonquian.atlas-ling.ca/ Proto-Algonquian online dictionary]\n*[[ethnologuefamily:682-16|Algonquian languages]] - [[Ethnologue]] page\n*[http://www.native-languages.org/famalg.htm Native Languages of the Americas: Algonquian Language Family]\n*[https://www.mun.ca/linguistics/research/language/protoAlgonkian/ Proto-Algonkian Roots and Word Formatives] by John Hewson\n*[http://proalki.uni-leipzig.de/w/images/a/ac/Pra_Handout_PA.pdf Proto-Algonquian] - handout by Daniela Henze (2010)\n*[http://home.kpn.nl/cvkolmes/ojibwe/corrCrOj.htm Correspondences of Ojibwe, Cree, and Proto-Algonquian sounds]\n\n{{Algonquian languages}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Proto-Algonquian Language}}\n[[Category:Algonquian languages]]\n[[Category:Algic languages]]\n[[Category:Proto-languages|Algonquian]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language\n| name             = Proto-Algonquian\n| familycolor      = American\n| fam1             = [[Algic languages|Algic]]\n| fam2             = [[Proto-Algic language|Proto-Algic]]\n| notice           = IPA\n|isoexception=protolanguage\n}}\n'''Proto-Algonquian''' (commonly abbreviated '''PA''') is the [[proto-language]] from which the various [[Algonquian languages]] are descended. It is generally estimated to have been spoken around 2,500 to 3,000 years ago,{{sfn|Goddard|1978|p=587}} but on the question of where it was spoken, there is less agreement. The Algonquian family, which is a branch of the larger [[Algic languages|Algic language family]], is usually divided into three subgroups: [[Eastern Algonquian languages|Eastern Algonquian]], which is a [[historical linguistics|genetic]] subgroup, and [[Central Algonquian languages|Central Algonquian]] and [[Plains Algonquian languages|Plains Algonquian]], both of which are [[Sprachbund|areal]] groupings. In the historical linguistics of North America, Proto-Algonquian is one of the best studied, most thoroughly reconstructed proto-languages.{{sfn|Campbell|2004|p=185}}{{sfn|Goddard|1979|p=70}} It is descended from [[Proto-Algic]].\n\n==History of research==\nMost Algonquian languages are similar enough that their relatedness has been recognized for centuries and was commented on by the early English and French colonists and explorers. For example, in 1787 (over a decade before [[William Jones (philologist)#Scholarly contributions|Sir William Jones' famous speech]] on Indo-European), the theologian and linguist [[Jonathan Edwards (the younger)|Jonathan Edwards Jr.]] deduced that the Algonquian languages of the eastern and central United States were \"radically the same\" ('radically' meaning having a common 'root', since ''radix'' is Latin for 'root'), and contrasted them with the neighboring [[Iroquoian languages]].{{sfn|Campbell|1997|pp=29-30}} The earliest work on reconstructing the Algonquian proto-language was undertaken by the linguists [[Truman Michelson]] and [[Leonard Bloomfield]]. In 1925 Bloomfield reconstructed what he called \"Primitive Central Algonquian\", using what were at the time the four best-attested Algonquian languages: [[Fox language|Fox]], [[Ojibwe language|Ojibwe]], [[Menominee language|Menominee]], and [[Plains Cree language|Plains Cree]].{{sfn|Thomason|2006|pp=190-191}} Following his initial reconstructions, investigations of other languages revealed that his \"Primitive Central Algonquian\" was essentially equivalent to Proto-Algonquian.{{sfn|Bloomfield|1946|pp=85-86}} Bloomfield wrote a refinement and expansion of his reconstruction in 1946, and his two papers remain the starting point for all research and reconstructions of Proto-Algonquian.{{sfn|Thomason|2006|pp=190-191}}{{sfn|Goddard|1979|p=70-71}} In the years since there has been an enormous amount of comparative work undertaken on the Algonquian family.{{sfn|Goddard|1990|p=99}}\n\n==Urheimat==\nThere remains some disagreement over the Algonquian ''[[Urheimat]]'' (homeland of the protolanguage). The initial theory, first put forth by [[Frank T. Siebert, Jr.]] in 1967 based on examining of the ranges of numerous species of plants and animals for which reliable Algonquian [[cognate]]s existed, holds that Proto-Algonquian was spoken between [[Georgian Bay, Ontario|Georgian Bay]] and [[Lake Ontario]], in [[Ontario]], Canada, and at least as far south as [[Niagara Falls]]. Research a generation later suggests that in fact it was spoken farther west than this, perhaps \"somewhere immediately west of [[Lake Superior]].\"{{sfn|Goddard|1994|p=207}}\n\n==Phonology==\n===Vowels===\nProto-Algonquian had four basic vowels, ''*i'', ''*e'', ''*a'', ''*o'', each of which had a [[Vowel length|long]] counterpart (commonly written ''*i\u00b7'', ''*e\u00b7'', ''*a\u00b7'', ''*o\u00b7''), for a total of eight vowels. The same inventory of eight vowels was found in Proto-Algic, but Proto-Algonquian did not inherit its inventory directly from Proto-Algic. Rather, several sound changes left pre-Proto-Algonquian without short *''i'' and *''o''.<ref name=\"Proulx 2004 vowels\">Paul Proulx, ''Proto-Algic VI: Conditioned Yurok reflexes of Proto-Algic vowels'', ''Kansas Working Papers in Linguistics'' 27:124\u2013138 (2004)</ref> It is not clear that they had redeveloped by the time of Proto-Algonquian. All instances in which Bloomfield reconstructed ''*o'' can now be reconstructed as ''*we'' based on evidence from some of the Eastern languages (for example, Bloomfield's ''*nekotwi'' \"one\" is now reconstructed as ''*nekwetwi'' based on forms like [[Munsee language|Munsee]] ''nkw\u00fati'').{{sfn|Goddard|1979|p=75}} There are still a handful of instances where ''*o'' can be reconstructed, usually as the result of a [[Morphophonology|morphophonological]] process of vowel shortening. Goddard concludes that \"an independent phoneme ''*o'' is of no great antiquity in Proto-Algonquian\",{{sfn|Goddard|1979|p=75}} but recommends continuing to use it in reconstructions. Likewise, Berman states that \"PA ''*i'' is probably also of recent origin\", derived from earlier (pre-Proto-Algonquian) ''*ye'' sequences and morphophonological shortening.{{sfn|Berman|1982|p=414}}\n\n===Consonants===\nProto-Algonquian had a smaller number of consonants than Proto-Algic. The reconstructed consonants are as follows (given in the [[Americanist phonetic notation]] common in the literature):{{sfn|Thomason|2006|p=191}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+PA Consonant Phonemes\n|-\n! colspan=2|\n! align=\"center\"|[[Labial consonant|Labial]]\n! align=\"center\"|[[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n! align=\"center\"|[[Palatal consonant|Palatal]]/<br>[[Postalveolar consonant|Postalveolar]]\n! align=\"center\"|[[Velar consonant|Velar]]\n! align=\"center\"|[[Glottal consonant|Glottal]]\n|-\n! colspan=2|[[Plosive consonant|Plosive]]\n| align=\"center\"|'''p'''\n| align=\"center\"|'''t'''\n| align=\"center\"|'''\u010d''' {{IPA|[t\u0283]}}\n| align=\"center\"|'''k'''\n|\n|-\n! rowspan=2|[[Fricative consonant|Fricative]]\n! Central\n|\n| align=\"center\"|'''s'''\n| align=\"center\"|'''\u0161''' {{IPA|[\u0283]}}\n| align=\"center\"|\n| align=\"center\"|'''h'''\n|-\n! Possible [[Lateral consonant|Lateral]]\n|\n| align=\"center\"|'''\u03b8 or \u026c'''\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! rowspan=3|[[Sonorant consonant|Sonorant]]\n! [[Nasal stop|Nasal]]\n| align=\"center\"|'''m'''\n| align=\"center\"|'''n'''\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! [[Approximant]]\n| align=\"center\"|'''w'''\n| align=\"center\"|'''r or l'''\n| align=\"center\"|'''y''' {{IPA|[j]}}\n|\n|\n|}\n\nThe phoneme given in the table as \u27e8r\u27e9 was reconstructed by Bloomfield as ''*l'', but Goddard has more recently argued that it should be reconstructed as ''*r'', largely because the earliest attestations of the majority of languages show some sort of rhotic as its reflex, which in many languages subsequently changed to a lateral within the historical period.{{sfn|Goddard|1994|p=204-205}} The precise pronunciation of the phoneme written \u27e8\u03b8\u27e9 is unknown. It has merged with the reflex of ''*r'' in all Algonquian languages except for [[Cree language|Cree]] and the [[Arapahoan languages]].{{sfn|Bloomfield|1946|p=87}}{{sfn|Pentland|2006|p=163}} [[Leonard Bloomfield]] originally suggested that it could have been either an [[interdental]] fricative or a [[Voiceless lateral fricative|lateral fricative]]. One piece of evidence for the interdental fricative is that this is the reflex it has in Arapaho.{{sfn|Goddard|1994|p=204-205}} However, other researchers have argued for its reconstruction as a lateral fricative, {{IPA|*/\u026c/}}, in part because of the aforementioned merger in most languages with the phoneme traditionally reconstructed as ''*l''.{{sfn|Picard|1984|p=}}\n\nAs with ''*i'' and ''*o'', it is unclear whether ''*\u010d'' was an independent phoneme in Proto-Algonquian. Almost all instances where ''*\u010d'' is reconstructed are before ''*i'', ''*i\u00b7'', or ''*y'', where it does not contrast with ''*t'' (see below), or are cases of diminutive consonant symbolism.{{sfn|Pentland|2006|p=163}} However, Goddard recommends continuing to write it in reconstructions, since it seems to have been present in the clusters ''*\u010dp'' and ''*\u010dk''; since it can be reconstructed before ''*a'' in the term ''*\u010dapo\u00b7nk-'' \"splash\"; and since ''*t'' does appear before ''*i\u00b7'' in some reconstructions of the onomatopoeic noun ''ti\u00b7nti\u00b7wa'' \"blue jay\" (however, see [[:wikt:Appendix:Proto-Algonquian/ti\u00b7nti\u00b7wa|Wiktionary]] for more).{{sfn|Goddard|1979|pp=73-74}}\n\n===Clusters===\nReconstruction of the consonant clusters has been relatively difficult, and the paths the clusters take in their evolutions to the daughter languages have been complex. The current view is that the permissible consonant clusters were (first member on the left, second member across the top):{{sfn|Thomason|2006|p=191}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+PA Consonant Clusters\n|-\n! \n! p\n! k\n! t\n! \u010d\n! \u03b8\n! s\n! \u0161\n! r\n! m\n|-\n! &nbsp; {{IPA|\u0294}} &nbsp;\n|\n|\n| align=\"center\"|''{{IPA|*\u0294}}t''\n| align=\"center\"|''{{IPA|*\u0294}}\u010d''\n| align=\"center\"|''{{IPA|*\u0294}}\u03b8''\n| align=\"center\"|''{{IPA|*\u0294}}s''\n| align=\"center\"|''{{IPA|*\u0294}}\u0161''\n| align=\"center\"|''{{IPA|*\u0294}}r''\n| rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|&nbsp;''*Hm''&nbsp;\n|-\n! h\n| align=\"center\"|&nbsp;''*hp''&nbsp;\n| align=\"center\"|&nbsp;''*hk''&nbsp;\n| align=\"center\"|&nbsp;''*ht''&nbsp;\n| align=\"center\"|&nbsp;''*h\u010d''&nbsp;\n| align=\"center\"|&nbsp;''*h\u03b8''&nbsp;\n| align=\"center\"|&nbsp;''*hs''&nbsp;\n| align=\"center\"|&nbsp;''*h\u0161''&nbsp;\n| align=\"center\"|&nbsp;''(*hr)''&nbsp;\n|-\n! N\n| align=\"center\"|''*mp''\n| align=\"center\"|''*nk''\n| align=\"center\"|''*nt''\n| align=\"center\"|''*n\u010d''\n| align=\"center\"|''*n\u03b8''\n| align=\"center\"|''*ns''\n| align=\"center\"|''*n\u0161''\n| align=\"center\"|''*nr''\n|\n|-\n! align=\"center\"|\u010d\n| align=\"center\"|''*\u010dp''\n| align=\"center\"|''*\u010dk''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! \u0161\n| align=\"center\"|''*\u0161p''\n| align=\"center\"|''*\u0161k''\n| align=\"center\"|&nbsp;''(*\u0161t)''&nbsp;\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! \u03b8\n| align=\"center\"|''*\u03b8p''\n| align=\"center\"|''*\u03b8k''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! x\n| align=\"center\"|''*xp''\n| align=\"center\"|''*xk''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! \u00e7\n| align=\"center\"|''*\u00e7p''\n| align=\"center\"|''*\u00e7k''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\nIn several cases the actual phonetic identity of the first member of the clusters was unknown, and Bloomfield's choice of symbols to represent them was purely arbitrary.{{sfn|Bloomfield|1946|p=88}} Thus, \u27e8x\u27e9 does not represent *[x], \u27e8\u00e7\u27e9 does not represent *[\u00e7], and \u27e8\u0294\u27e9 does not necessarily represent *[{{IPA|\u0294}}]. Goddard argues that Bloomfield's arbitrary symbol \u27e8x\u27e9 be reconstructed as ''*s'', and Bloomfield's \u27e8\u00e7\u27e9 be reconstructed as ''*r''.{{sfn|Goddard|1994b|pp=205-206}} While a glottal stop phoneme is not otherwise reconstructed, given that Bloomfield's \u27e8\u0294\u27e9 in clusters seems to represent the neutralization of ''*p'' and ''*k'' and its realization in Menominee and Cheyenne is a glottal stop, it probably was indeed phonetically {{IPA|[\u0294]}}.{{sfn|Goddard|1979|pp=77-78}}{{sfn|Thomason|2006|p=191}} The cluster written \u27e8Hm\u27e9 shows up as ''p'' or ''m'' in most of the daughter languages, but as ''hm'' in [[Munsee language|Munsee]] (for example, PA ''*wi\u00b7kiwa\u00b7Hmi'' \"house\" becomes Ojibwe ''wiigiwaam'', Fox ''w\u00eekiy\u00e2pi'', and Munsee ''w\u00edikwahm'').{{sfn|Goddard|1967|p=87}}{{sfn|Goddard|1974b|pp=326-327}} The first member of the cluster may have been either *h or {{IPA|*\u0294}}.{{sfn|Goddard|1974b|pp=322}}\n\nThe clusters ''*\u0161t'' and ''*hr'' are each reconstructed on the basis of only a single correspondence set (''*\u0161t'' in ''*we\u0161tikwa\u00b7ni'', \"his/her head\"; and ''*hr'' in ''*re\u00b7hre\u00b7wa'', \"s/he breathes\"){{sfn|Goddard|1979|pp=71-72}}{{sfn|Pentland|1977|p=}} and may not have been part of Proto-Algonquian. David Pentland, for example, argued that Ojibwe ''oshtigwaan'', claimed as the only form requiring the reconstruction of ''*\u0161t'', is a borrowing from Cree.{{sfn|Pentland|1977|p=}} However, evidence from Munsee and [[Blackfoot language|Blackfoot]] seem to also point toward ''*\u0161t'' as a valid separate cluster in PA (Munsee ''w\u00ecil\u00f9sht\u00edikan'', Blackfoot ''mo\u2019tok\u00e1\u00e1ni'', \"head, hair\").{{sfn|Goddard|1979|p=107}}{{sfn|Berman|2006|p=282}}\n\nFinally, all consonants and consonant clusters could be followed by ''*w'' or ''*y'' (although the sequences ''*\u010dw'' and ''*hy'' did not occur; and ''*t'' and ''*\u03b8'' were regularly replaced before ''*y'', for which see below).{{sfn|Goddard|1979|p=72}}\n\n===Phonological processes===\nSeveral [[Allophone|allophonic]] processes, [[Morphophonology|morphophonemic]] processes, and [[Phonotactics|phonological constraints]] can be reconstructed. Among the most significant of these processes was that ''*t'' and ''*\u03b8'' became ''*\u010d'' and ''*\u0161'' respectively before ''*i'', ''*i\u00b7'', and ''*y''.{{sfn|Bloomfield|1946|p=92}} For example, the initial ''*went-'' \"from there\" (as in ''*wentenamwa'' \"s/he takes it from there\") is realized as ''*wen\u010d-'' in the word ''*wen\u010di\u00b7wa'' \"s/he comes from there\", since it precedes ''*i\u00b7''.{{sfn|Bloomfield|1946|pp=86, 89, 92}}\n\nThere were several restrictions on phonotactics and the shape of the PA word that can be reconstructed. All words began with a single consonant (other than ''*h'') or vowel, or with a consonant plus ''*w'' or ''*y''; there were no sequences of consecutive vowels; and the word always ended in a short vowel. The vowels ''*i'' and ''*o'' never occurred in initial syllables.{{sfn|Goddard|1979|p=72}} A sequence of consonant+semivowel could not be followed by ''*o'' or ''*o\u00b7''.{{sfn|Goddard|1974a|p=}} There was also a restriction which prevented two-syllable nouns from ending in a sequence of short vowel + consonant + short vowel.{{sfn|Berman|1992|p=}}\n\nIn most cases, when the pronominal prefixes ''*ne-'' (first person), ''*ke-'' (second person), and ''*we-'' (third person) were added to a vowel-initial stem, an [[Epenthesis|epenthetic]] ''*-t-'' was inserted between the prefix and the stem. Thus, the prefixes became ''*net-'', ''*ket-'', and ''*wet-'' respectively.{{sfn|Bloomfield|1946|p=95}} For example, ''*ne-'' + ''*-ehkwa-'' = ''*netehkwa-'' \"my louse\". This feature goes back to [[Proto-Algic]] (compare [[Wiyot language|Wiyot]] ''du-'' + ''h\u00edkw'' = ''dut\u00edkw'' \"my louse\").{{sfn|Campbell|Poser|2008|p=178}} There were a handful of irregular exceptions to this pattern, however. For example, the prefixes lost their vowels before several kinship terms, as in ''*ne-'' + ''*-o\u00b7hkomehsa'' = ''*no\u00b7hkomehsa'' \"my grandmother.\"{{sfn|Bloomfield|1946|pp=91, 96}}\n\n[[File:Algonquian langs.png|thumb|360px|Approximate distribution of the Algonquian languages when first encountered by Europeans]]\nSeveral rules for [[Sandhi|internal sandhi]] in morpheme combinations can be reconstructed. The most basic was the insertion of a \"connective i\" between two consonants. For example, ''*po\u00b7n-'' \"cease\" + ''*-m'' \"act by speech on an animate object\" = ''*po\u00b7n'''i'''me\u00b7wa'' \"s/he stops talking to him/her.\" {{sfn|Bloomfield|1946|pp=90-91}}{{sfn|Thomason|2006|p=192}} In a few idiosyncratic cases, however, this rule did not operate, and instead the consonants were changed in various ways. For instance, the combination ''\u03b8+p'' produced when the root ''*e\u03b8-'' \"thither, thus\" was added to the final ''*-pahto\u00b7'' \"run\" simplified to ''*xp'': ''*expahta\u00b7wa'' \"s/he runs thither.\" One regular exception to the \"connective i\" rule was when the conjunct suffix ''*-ki'' was added to a verb stem ending in a consonant, for example ''*ki\u00b7\u0161ekat-'' \"be day\" + ''*-ki'' = ''*ki\u00b7\u0161ekaxki'' \"when it is day.\" {{sfn|Bloomfield|1946|p=91}} Note that Bloomfield here actually reconstructed this word as ''*ki\u00b7\u0161eka\u03b8ki'', but evidence from other Algonquian languages has shown that the cluster should be reconstructed as ''*xk''.{{sfn|Proulx|1984a|p=168, note 2}} When two vowels became contiguous, if one was a long vowel and one was short, the short vowel dropped: ''*naka\u00b7-'' \"stop\" + ''*-en'' \"by hand\" = ''*naka\u00b7ne\u00b7wa'' \"s/he stops him/her by hand.\" If both were long, an epenthetic ''*y'' was inserted between the two.{{sfn|Bloomfield|1946|p=93}}\n\n==Grammar==\n{{More citations needed section|date=November 2011}}\nProto-Algonquian nouns had an [[Animacy|animate/inanimate]] contrast: nouns representing animate beings (and some traditional items viewed as having spiritual powers) were classed as ''animate'', while all other nouns were ''inanimate''. The plural marker differed in form depending on whether the noun was animate or inanimate: animate nouns took a plural suffix ''*-aki'', while inanimate nouns took a plural suffix ''*-ari''. Another important distinction involved the contrast between nouns marked as ''proximate'' and those marked as ''[[obviative]]''. Proximate nouns were those deemed most central or important to the discourse, while obviative nouns were those less important to the discourse. When two third person participants appeared in a sentence, one was marked as proximate and the other as obviative, in order to distinguish which one was the subject and which was the object (since verbs inflected for whether they had a proximate or obviative subject and a proximate or obviative object).  In a given stretch of discourse, there will not be two proximate or two obviative participants.{{sfn|Hockett|1966|p=60}}\n\nThere were personal pronouns which distinguished three persons, two numbers (singular and plural), [[Clusivity|inclusive and exclusive first person plural]], and proximate and obviative third persons. Demonstrative pronouns have been more difficult to reconstruct, as many of the daughter languages have innovated a great deal.\n\nPA had four classes of verbs: [[Transitive verb|transitive]] verbs with an animate object (abbreviated TA), transitive verbs with an inanimate object (TI), [[Intransitive verb|intransitive]] verbs with an animate subject (AI), and intransitive verbs with an inanimate subject (II). Transitive verbs had two paradigms, termed ''objective'' and ''absolute''. Objective verbs were used when the object of the verb was not present as an overt noun elsewhere in the sentence, while absolute verbs were used when the object of the verb ''was'' marked with an overt noun in the sentence. Objective verbs could also be used when an object was present, and in such cases indicated that the object was [[Definiteness|definite]], as opposed to indefinite.<ref>The verb system is surveyed by Hockett (1966) with particular reference to [[Potawatomi]];  see also Teeter (1965) and Weggelaar (1974).</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Algonquian languages]]\n**[[Plains Algonquian languages]]\n**[[Central Algonquian languages]]\n**[[Eastern Algonquian languages]]\n*[[Algic languages]]\n*[[Algonquian sound laws]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Berman|first=Howard |year=1982 |title=Two Phonological Innovations in Ritwan |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=48 |issue=4 |pages=412\u2013420 |jstor=1264843 |doi=10.1086/465750}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Berman|first=Howard |year=1990 |title=New Algonquian\u2013Ritwan Cognate Sets |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=56 |issue=3 |pages=431\u2013434 |jstor=1265518 |doi=10.1086/466168}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Berman|first=Howard |year=1992 |title=A Restriction on the Shape of Proto-Algonquian Nouns |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=58 |issue=3 |pages=321\u2013323 |jstor=3519790}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Berman|first=Howard |year=2006 |title=Studies in Blackfoot Prehistory |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=72 |issue=2 |pages=264\u2013284 |jstor= |doi=10.1086/507167}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Bloomfield|first=Leonard |authorlink=Leonard Bloomfield |year=1925 |title=On the Sound System of Central Algonquian |journal=[[Language (journal)|Language]] |volume=1 |issue=4 |pages=130\u2013156 |jstor=409540}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Bloomfield|first=Leonard |editor1-first=Harry |editor1-last=Hoijer |editor1-link=Harry Hoijer |editor2-last=Osgood |editor2-first=Cornelius|year=1946 |title=Linguistic Structures of Native America |contribution=Algonquian |series=Viking Fund Publications in Anthropology, 6 |place=New York |pages=85\u2013129 |asin=B002M3AJEA}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Campbell|first=Lyle |authorlink=Lyle Campbell |year=1997 |title=American Indian Languages: The Historical Linguistics of Native America |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-509427-5}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Campbell|first=Lyle |year=2004 |title=Historical Linguistics: An Introduction |edition=2nd |publisher=The MIT Press |place=Cambridge, MA |isbn=978-0-262-53267-9}}\n*{{Cite book |last1=Campbell|first1=Lyle |last2=Poser|first2=William J. |authorlink2=William Poser |year=2008 |title=Language Classification: History and Method |publisher=Cambridge University Press |place=Cambridge |isbn=978-0-521-88005-3 |lastauthoramp=y}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Goddard|first=Ives |authorlink=Ives Goddard |year=1967 |title=Contributions to Anthropology: Linguistics I (Algonquian) |contribution=The Algonquian Independent Indicative |publisher=National Museum of Canada, Bulletin 214 |place=Ottawa |series=Anthropological Series 78 |pages=66\u2013106 |oclc=102526}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Goddard|first=Ives |year=1974a |title=An Outline of the Historical Phonology of Arapaho and Atsina |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=40 |issue=2 |pages=102\u2013116 |jstor=1264344 |doi=10.1086/465292}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Goddard|first=Ives |year=1974b |title=Remarks on the Algonquian Independent Indicative |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=40 |issue=4 |pages=317\u2013327 |jstor=1265006 |doi=10.1086/465328}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Goddard|first=Ives |year=1978 |chapter=Central Algonquian Languages |editor-last=Trigger |editor-first=Bruce G. |editor2=William C. Sturtevant |volume=15 |title=Handbook of North American Indians: Northeast |pages=583\u2013587 |publisher=Smithsonian Institution |place=Washington, D.C. |isbn=978-0-16-004575-2}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Goddard |first=Ives |year=1979 |editor1-first=Lyle |editor1-last=Campbell |editor2-first=Marianne |editor2-last=Mithun |title=The Languages of Native America: Historical and Comparative Assessment |contribution=Comparative Algonquian |pages=[https://archive.org/details/languagesofnativ0000unse/page/70 70\u2013132] |publisher=University of Texas Press |place=Austin |isbn=978-0-292-74624-4 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/languagesofnativ0000unse/page/70 }}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Goddard|first=Ives |year=1982 |title=The Historical Phonology of Munsee |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=48 |issue=1 |pages=16\u201328 |jstor=1264746 |doi=10.1086/465711}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Goddard|first=Ives |year=1990 |editor-first=Philip |editor-last=Baldi |editor-link=Philip Baldi |title=Linguistic Change and Reconstruction Methodology |contribution=Algonquian Linguistic Change and Reconstruction |series=Trends in Linguistics: Studies and Monographs 45 |publisher=Mouton de Gruyter |place=Berlin |pages=99\u2013114 |isbn=978-0-89925-546-0}}\n*{{Cite conference |title=A New Look for Algonquian |last=Goddard|first=Ives |year=1994a |conference=Comparative Linguistics Workshop, University of Pittsburgh, April 9}}\n*{{Cite conference |title=The West-to-East Cline in Algonquian Dialectology |last=Goddard|first=Ives |booktitle=Actes du Vingt-Cinqui\u00e8me Congr\u00e8s des Algonquinistes |editor=Cowan, William |pages=187\u2013211 |year=1994b |publisher=Carleton University |place=Ottawa |issn=0831-5671 |oclc=11194820}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Hockett|first=Charles F.|year=1966|title=What Algonquian is Really Like|journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=31 |issue=1|pages=59\u201373|jstor=1263449}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Michelson|first=Truman |authorlink=Truman Michelson |year=1935 |title=Phonetic Shifts in Algonquian Languages |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=8 |issue=3/4 |pages=131\u2013171 |jstor=1263140 |doi=10.1086/463813}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Miller|first=Wick R. |year=1959 |title=An Outline of Shawnee Historical Phonology |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=25 |issue=1 |pages=16\u201321 |jstor=1263919 |doi=10.1086/464490}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Mithun|first=Marianne |authorlink=Marianne Mithun |year=1999 |title=The Languages of Native North America |publisher=Cambridge University Press |place=Cambridge |isbn=978-0-521-23228-9}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Pentland|first=David H. |year=1977 |title=Proto-Algonquian *\u0161t |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=43 |issue=3 |pages=225\u2013226 |jstor=1264417 |doi=10.1086/465484}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Pentland|first=David H. |contribution=Algonquian and Ritwan Languages |title=Encyclopedia of Language & Linguistics |edition=2nd |volume=1 |pages=161\u2013166 |year=2006 |publisher=Elsevier |place=Oxford |doi=10.1016/B0-08-044854-2/02265-3}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Picard|first=Marc |year=1984 |title=On the Naturalness of Algonquian {{IPA|\u026c}} |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=50 |issue=4 |pages=424\u2013437 |jstor=1265401 |doi=10.1086/465851}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Proulx|first=Paul |year=1977 |title=Connective Vowels in Proto-Algonquian |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=43 |issue=2 |pages=156\u2013157 |jstor=1264935 |doi=10.1086/465473}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Proulx|first=Paul |year=1980 |title=The Subordinative Order of Proto-Algonquian |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=46 |issue=4 |pages=289\u2013300 |jstor=1264710 |doi=10.1086/465664}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Proulx|first=Paul |year=1982 |title=The Origin of the Absolute Verbs of the Algonquian Independent Order |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=48 |issue=4 |pages=394\u2013411 |jstor=1264842 |doi=10.1086/465749}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Proulx|first=Paul |year=1984a |title=Proto-Algic I: Phonological Sketch |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=50 |issue=2 |pages=165\u2013207 |jstor=1265603 |doi=10.1086/465826}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Proulx|first=Paul |year=1984b |title=Algonquian Objective Verbs |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=50 |issue=4 |pages=403\u2013423 |jstor=1265400 |doi=10.1086/465850}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Proulx|first=Paul |year=1989 |title=A Sketch of Blackfoot Historical Phonology |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=55 |issue=1 |pages=43\u201382 |jstor=1265411 |doi=10.1086/466104}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Siebert Jr.|first=Frank T. |title=Certain Proto-Algonquian Consonant Clusters |journal=Language |year=1941 |volume=17 |issue=4 |pages=298\u2013303 |doi=10.2307/409280 |jstor=409280 |publisher=Linguistic Society of America}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Siebert Jr.|first=Frank T. |title=Contributions to Anthropology: Linguistics I (Algonquian) |contribution=The Original Home of the Proto-Algonquian People |publisher=National Museum of Canada, Bulletin 214 |year=1967 |place=Ottawa |series=Anthropological Series 78 |pages=13\u201347 |oclc=102526}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Teeter|first=Karl V. |authorlink=Karl V. Teeter |year=1965 |title=The Algonquian Verb: Notes Toward a Reconsideration |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=31 |issue=3 |pages=221\u2013225 |jstor=1263896 |doi=10.1086/464840}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Thomason|first=Lucy |contribution=Proto-Algonkian Phonology and Morpho-Syntax |title=Encyclopedia of Language & Linguistics |edition=2nd |volume=10 |pages=190\u2013198 |year=2006 |publisher=Elsevier |place=Oxford |doi=10.1016/B0-08-044854-2/01896-4}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Weggelaar, C. |year=1974 |title=The Algonquian Verb: Another Reconsideration |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |volume=40 |issue=3 |pages=249\u2013253 |jstor=1264864 |doi=10.1086/465316}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://protoalgonquian.atlas-ling.ca/ Proto-Algonquian online dictionary]\n*[[ethnologuefamily:682-16|Algonquian languages]] - [[Ethnologue]] page\n*[http://www.native-languages.org/famalg.htm Native Languages of the Americas: Algonquian Language Family]\n*[https://www.mun.ca/linguistics/research/language/protoAlgonkian/ Proto-Algonkian Roots and Word Formatives] by John Hewson\n*[http://proalki.uni-leipzig.de/w/images/a/ac/Pra_Handout_PA.pdf Proto-Algonquian] - handout by Daniela Henze (2010)\n*[http://home.kpn.nl/cvkolmes/ojibwe/corrCrOj.htm Correspondences of Ojibwe, Cree, and Proto-Algonquian sounds]\n\n{{Algonquian languages}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Proto-Algonquian Language}}\n[[Category:Algonquian languages]]\n[[Category:Algic languages]]\n[[Category:Proto-languages|Algonquian]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eVowels:Journal cites:, templated 1 journal cites", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proto-Algonquian_language"}
{"title_page": "The Growlers", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = The Growlers\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = [[File:The_Growlers_Live_Beach_Goth_Tour.jpg|250px|center|alt=The Growlers playing at Beach Goth 2018]]\n| caption          = The Growlers playing at Beach Goth 2018\n| landscape        = no\n| genre            = [[Surf rock]], [[psychedelic rock]], [[garage rock]]\n| years_active     = 2006\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist| \n*Beach Goth Records and Tapes\n*[[Cult Records]]\n*[[Everloving Records]]\n*[[Burger Records]]\n*[[FatCat Records]]\n*Palmist\n*Ayo Silver\n*Smack Face\n}}  \n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist| \n*[[Julian Casablancas]]\n*[[Kirin J. Callinan]]\n*[[Dan Auerbach]]\n*[[Delicate Steve]]\n*[[Allah-Las]]\n*[[Jonathan Richman]]\n*[[The Grand Elegance]]\n*The Abigails\n*Tomorrow's Tulips\n}}\n| website          = {{URL|thegrowlers.com}}\n| current_members  = Brooks Nielsen<br />Matt Taylor<br />Kyle Straka<br />Brad Bowers<br />Adam Wolcott Smith<br />Richard Gowen\n| past_members     = Brian Stewart<br />Warren Thomas<br />Patrick Palomo<br /> Clark Davison<br /> Miles Patterson<br />Zachary Aguirre<br />Scott Montoya<br />Anthony Braun Perry<br /> Jason Kaiser\n}}\n\n'''The Growlers''' are an American band from Southern California . They began their career in the [[Orange County, California|Orange County]] city of [[Dana Point, California]] in 2006. They are currently based in [[Costa Mesa]].<ref name=\"Reynolds\">Reynolds, Wyoming (2018) \"[https://ocweekly.com/the-growlers-hope-beach-goths-la-shift-leads-to-its-salvation/ The Growlers Hope Beach Goth's LA Shift Leads To Its Salvation]\", ''[[OC Weekly]]'', August 1, 2018.</ref> The band is currently composed of singer Brooks Nielsen, lead guitarist Matt Taylor and keyboard player/guitarist Kyle Straka.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.therooster.com/blog/growlers-drinking-whiskey-tripping-out-and-getting-weird-living|title=The Growlers: Drinking whiskey, tripping out and getting weird for a living.|last=|first=|date=January 7, 2013|website=the rooster.com|publisher=|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> They have released seven albums, several EPs and a number of singles. The band's sound has been described as \"a trademark style of music that somehow combines surf, pop, rock and beat\" which has been labeled \"Beach Goth\".<ref name=\"Keller\">Keller, Brandy (2010) \"[http://www.spinner.com/2010/03/14/the-growlers-interview-sxsw-2010/ The Growlers Interview: SXSW 2010]\", spinner.com, March 14, 2010, retrieved January 28, 2012</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nSinger Brooks Nielsen and music director/guitarist Matt Taylor met in high school in the beach town of Dana Point, California, bonding over surfing, skating, and partying.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smashboxstudios.com/hype/growlers-southern-californias-beach-goth-beatles-mania/|title=The Growlers are Southern California\u2019s Beach Goth Beatles, Mania and All|last=Salek|first=Yassi|date=November 4, 2014|website=smashboxstudios.com|publisher=|language=en-GB}}</ref> When offered the chance to perform at a house party, the duo quickly wrote their first six songs in a single day, leading to the first incarnation of the band that would eventually become The Growlers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.laweekly.com/the-growlers-have-a-shot-at-the-big-time-but-it-makes-them-feel-a-bit-uneasy/|title=The Growlers Have a Shot at the Big Time, But it Makes Them Feel a Bit Uneasy|last=Flanders|first=Kai|date=April 19, 2012|website=laweekly.com|publisher=|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\nAfter releasing a handful of self-recorded cassettes and CDs, The Growlers issued their first studio album, ''Are You in or Out?'' in 2009 on Everloving Records. Aquarium Drunkard described it as \u201cconsistent in sound and tone that is as enjoyable straight through or on shuffle\u2026 Taken as a whole, the record is a beautiful mix of late 60\u2019s freak-out, folk calmness and surf rock.\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aquariumdrunkard.com/2009/10/05/the-growlers-are-you-in-or-out/|title=The Growlers :: Are You In Or Out?|last=Kramer|first=B=October 5, 2009|website=aquariumdrunkard.com|publisher=|language=en-GB}}</ref> Their second album, ''Hot Tropics'', was released in 2010, also on Everloving Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thegrowlers.com/about|title=Growlers: About|accessdate=October 31, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111024192555/http://thegrowlers.com/about|archivedate=October 24, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.phoenixnewtimes.com/uponsun/2011/04/qa_the_growlers_brooks_nielsen.php|title=Q&A: The Growlers' Brooks Nielsen Talks Getting Drunk, Being Weird and Bill Murray|work=Phoenix New Times|accessdate=June 4, 2013}}</ref> The band's third album, ''[[Hung at Heart]]'', the first to feature Anthony Braun Perry on bass and Jason Kaiser on percussion, was released in 2013.<ref name=\"everloving.com\">[http://www.everloving.com/site/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=736:hung-at-heart&catid=1&Itemid=100004 Hung At Heart]. Everloving.com (November 8, 2012). Retrieved on December 14, 2013.</ref> The band originally worked with [[Dan Auerbach]] to record the album, but the finished version never saw official release. Instead the band recorded a new version of the album in Costa Mesa, CA with Mike McHugh at his Distillery Recording Studio, to get a more lo-fi sound. \n\n''[[Chinese Fountain]]'', their new \"more grown up, well polished\" album was released September 23, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://greatescapefestival.com/artist-interview-the-growlers/|title=Artist Interview: The Growlers|work=The Great Escape|access-date=March 24, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141108093203/http://greatescapefestival.com/artist-interview-the-growlers/|archive-date=November 8, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> This album was produced by JP Plunier at Seahorse Studios in Los Angeles, CA. While touring the album, the band expanded their live band with percussionist [[Nick Murray (musician)|Nick Murray]]. <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://guide.originalfuzz.com/articles/five-minutes-with-nick-murray|title=5 Minutes With Nick Murray|newspaper=Original Fuzz|access-date=October 11, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610174705/http://guide.originalfuzz.com/articles/five-minutes-with-nick-murray|archivedate=June 10, 2016}}</ref> <ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SNmFGKP3tAo YouTube ~ ''the Growlers (Live on KEXP)'']</ref>\n\nThe band's fifth studio album, ''[[City Club (album)|City Club]]'' was released by [[Cult Records]] on September 30, 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/julian-casablancas/96356|title=Listen to Julian Casablancas-produced new single by The Growlers|last=Earls|first=John|date=September 12, 2016|website=nme.com|publisher=|language=en-GB|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> while they embarked on a supporting tour in the same month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2016/07/cult-records-announces-new-growlers-album-fall-tou.html|title=Cult Records Announces New Growlers Album, Fall Tour|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> It was the first Growlers album to be credited solely to Brooks Nielsen and Matt Taylor, as opposed to the whole band.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.ascap.com/aceclient/AceWeb/#ace/search/workID/891050161|title=ACE Repertory|last=ACE|website=mobile.ascap.com|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> Nielsen and Taylor wrote and recorded demos for the album over a span of 2 to 3 months with the help of Kyle Mullarky at his studio in Topanga Canyon, CA. It was preceded by the title track as a single produced by [[Julian Casablancas]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/08/the-growlers-share-julian-casablancas-produced-single-city-club-listen/|title=The Growlers share Julian Casablancas-produced single \u201cCity Club\u201d \u2014 listen|date=August 26, 2016|language=en-US|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> who also owns the label.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bkmag.com/2016/09/16/brooks-nielsen-on-the-growlers-new-julian-casablancas-produced-album-city-club-cult-records/|title=The Growlers' Brooks Nielsen On New Julian Casablancas-Produced Album|last=Romano|first=Evan|date=September 16, 2016|website=Brooklyn Magazine|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> Neither drummer Scott Montoya nor bass player Anthony Perry feature on the album.<ref>http://www.allmusic.com/album/city-club-mw0002976520/credits</ref> On September 25, the band confirmed Montoya's departure from the band and stated that Perry was set to return in the near future.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/losGrowlers/posts/10153840189555079|title=The GROWLERS - Timeline {{!}} Facebook|website=www.facebook.com|access-date=October 11, 2016}}</ref> The band toured for this album with Brad Bowers on bass, Adam Wolcott Smith on keyboard, and Richard Gowen on drums.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://first-avenue.com/performer/growlers|title=The Growlers: First Avenue|access-date=March 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kcrw.com/people/the-growlers|title=The Growlers: KRCW|access-date=March 13, 2017}}</ref> Whether their membership in the band is permanent is currently unclear.\n\nThe band released ''[[Casual Acquaintances]]'' on July 27, 2018, a collection of demos and unused material from the City Club sessions.  \n\nThe Growlers have toured with artists such as [[The Black Keys]], [[Devendra Banhart]], Julian Casablancas, [[Night Beats]], and [[Jonathan Richman]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dothebay.com/p/interview-the-growlers|title=INTERVIEW + GIVEAWAY: THE GROWLERS|last=Gomez|first=Dominique|date=2016|website=Do The Bay|publisher=|access-date=June 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Cody Peterson |url=http://omahype.com/event/the-night-beats-w-the-growlers-snake-island/ |title=Omahype |publisher=Omahype |date= |accessdate=June 4, 2013}}</ref> They have also appeared at numerous festivals including Coachella, Bonnaroo, Primavera Sound, Lollapalooza, Austin City Limits, Sasquatch!, Wakarusa, Treasure Island, Fun Fun Fun, Bestival, Way Out West, End of The Road, Burgerama III, [[Rock in Rio]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/rock-in-rio/2011/noticia/2011/10/marcelo-camelo-e-growlers-fazem-show-morno-no-palco-sunset.html|title=Marcelo Camelo e The Growlers fazem show morno no Palco Sunset|publisher=G1.globo.com|accessdate=June 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com.br/noticia/marcelo-camelo-e-growlers-no-rock-rio/|title=Marcelo Camelo e The Growlers unem for\u00e7as no Rock in Rio|publisher=Rolling Stone|accessdate=June 4, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425064633/http://www.rollingstone.com.br/noticia/marcelo-camelo-e-growlers-no-rock-rio/|archive-date=April 25, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Outside Lands Music and Arts Festival|Outside Lands]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/2013/08/outside-lands-2013-best-things-day-two-saturday-nine-inch-nails-phoenix/|title=Outside Lands 2013: The 10 Best Things We Saw On Saturday|last=|first=|date=August 11, 2013|website=SPIN|publisher=|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Beach Goth==\n\nThe band has organized their annual Beach Goth festival since 2012. The event typically features performances by bands representing a variety of genres, including [[pop music|pop]], [[rap]], [[hip hop]], [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]], and [[rock music|rock]]. Over the years, the event has included costume contests, amusement park rides, and live performances of [[Rocky Horror Picture Show]]. The Growlers have headlined both Saturday and Sunday night of the annual Beach Goth festival since its inception.\n\nThe likes of [[Die Antwoord]], [[Grimes (musician)|Grimes]], [[Gucci Mane]], [[Julian Casablancas]], [[Mac DeMarco]], [[The Drums]], [[Foxygen]], [[White Arrows]] and [[Ghost B.C.]] have appeared at the festival.\n\nBeach Goth 4 (October 2015) was hosted by [[Pauly Shore]] and featured live performances of [[Rocky Horror Picture Show]] throughout the weekend as well as a performance of [[The Doors]] song \"People Are Strange\" by The Growlers and [[Julian Casablancas]].\n\nThe 2016 edition of Beach Goth took place at The Observatory in Santa Ana, CA on October 23\u201324, 2016.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/10/beach-goth-2016-festival-review-and-gallery/|title=Beach Goth 2016 Festival Review and Gallery|date=October 25, 2016|newspaper=Consequence of Sound|language=en-US|access-date=November 25, 2016}}</ref> It was originally scheduled to take place at the Oak Canyon Park but was moved last minute due to unexplained circumstances. The festival's lineup included [[Bon Iver]], [[TLC (group)|TLC]], [[James Blake (musician)|James Blake]], [[2 Live Crew]], [[Violent Femmes]], [[Future Islands]], [[Reel Big Fish]], [[The Faint]], [[the Pharcyde]], [[Left\u00f6ver Crack]], and [[DJ Quik]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stereogum.com/1887764/beach-goth-2016-lineup/news/|title=Beach Goth 2016 Lineup|date=July 13, 2016|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> While it was hailed a success, the outdoor festival suffered from rain and resultant street flooding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-beach-goth-20161020-snap-story.html|title=Beach Goth's lineup had the goods, but fest may not be ready for its close-up|last=Brown|first=August|website=latimes.com|access-date=November 25, 2016}}</ref> This caused the Growlers to delay their own set due to equipment damage.<ref name=\":0\" /> In the aftermath, the band issued an apology.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDue to an ongoing lawsuit with Noise Group (owners of The Observatory venue) over the Beach Goth trademark,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ocweekly.com/beach-goth-is-dead-the-observatory-suing-the-growlers-only-confirms-it-7660356/|title=Beach Goth is Dead. The Observatory Suing The Growlers Only Confirms It|date=November 15, 2016|work=OC Weekly|access-date=August 17, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> 2017's festival took on the name \"The Growlers Six\", which took place on October 28 & 29 at the LA Waterfront. The festival included artists such as the Yeah Yeah Yeahs, Modest Mouse, and the Butthole Surfers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/08/yeah-yeah-yeahs-modest-mouse-butthole-surfers-to-play-the-growlers-six-festival/|title=Yeah Yeah Yeahs, Modest Mouse, Butthole Surfers to play The Growlers Six Festival|date=August 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Growlers returned to their trademarked \"Beach Goth\" brand name for the 7th annual festival, taking place at the Los Angeles Historic State Park on August 5, 2018. Beach Goth 7 hosted performances by The Growlers, [[Jonathan Richman]], [[The Voidz]], [[The Drums]], [[La Luz (band)|La Luz]], and [[Gwar|GWAR]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://buzzbands.la/2018/08/03/beach-goth-7-here-are-your-set-times-for-sunday/|title=Beach Goth 7: Here are your set times for Sunday \u2013 buzzbands.la|date=August 3, 2018|work=buzzbands.la|access-date=August 17, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|The Growlers discography}}\n\n===Studio Albums===\n*''Are You In or Out?'' (2009), Everloving Records\n*''Hot Tropics'' (2010), Everloving Records\n*''[[Hung at Heart]]'' (2013), Everloving Records (US), FatCat Records (UK & Europe), Smack Face Records (Australia & New Zealand)\n*''[[Chinese Fountain]]'' (2014), Everloving Records (US), FatCat Records (UK & Europe), Smack Face Records (Australia & New Zealand)\n*[[City Club (album)|''City Club'']] (2016), Cult Records (US/EU)\n*''Natural Affair'' (2019), Beach Goth Records & Tapes\n\n===EPs===\n*''Split Growlers/Thee Ludds'' (2011), Palmist, limited to 500 copies<ref>[http://www.palmistrecords.com/?p=851 GROWLERS/ THEE LUDDS SPLIT 12\u2033 OUT TODAY IN UK/ EUROPE | Palmist]. Palmistrecords.com (October 3, 2011). Retrieved on December 14, 2013.</ref>\n*''Gay Thoughts/Uncle Sam's a Dick'' (2013), Ayo Silver<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ayosilver.bigcartel.com/product/the-growlers-gay-thoughts-uncle-sam-s-a-dick|title=Ayo Silver!|work=bigcartel.com}}</ref>\n*''Gilded Pleasures''  (2013), Everloving Records (US), Smack Face Records (Australia & New Zealand)\n*''Lonely This Christmas'' (2017), Beach Goth Records & Tapes\n\n===Other Releases===\n*''Greatest Hits'' (2007), self-released\n*[[Casual Acquaintances (The Growlers album)|''Casual Acquaintances'']] (2018) Beach Goth Records & Tapes (US)\n\n===Singles===\n*\"Gay Thoughts\" / \"Feeling Good\" (2011), Everloving, limited to 1000 copies on 7\" vinyl<ref>[http://www.everloving.com/site/index.php?option=com_wrapper&view=wrapper&Itemid=100086 Vinyl Shop]. Everloving.com. Retrieved on December 14, 2013.</ref>\n*\"Uncle Sam's a Dick\" / \"Drinking Song for Kids\" (2012), no label, limited to 500 copies, of which 250 each were sold online and at concerts on 7\" vinyl<ref>{{cite web|url=http://store.cinderblock.com/uncle-sam-s-a-dick-7-vinyl.html|title=Uncle Sam's a dick (7\")|website=cinderblock|accessdate=January 14, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026024625/http://store.cinderblock.com/uncle-sam-s-a-dick-7-vinyl.html|archivedate=October 26, 2012}}</ref>\n*\"Late Bloomers\" (2017), Cult Records LLC\n*\"Monotonia\" (2017), Beach Goth Records & Tapes\n*\"California\" (2017), Beach Goth Records & Tapes\n*\u201dWho Loves The Scum?\u201d (2018), Beach Goth Records  & Tapes\n*\"Natural Affair\" (2019), Beach Goth Records & Tapes\n*\"Foghorn Town\" (2019), Beach Goth Records & Tapes\n*\"Try Hard Fool\" (2019), Beach Goth Records & Tapes\n*\"Pulp Of Youth\" (2019), Beach Goth Records & Tapes\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://thegrowlers.com/}}\n\n{{The Growlers}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Growlers, The}}\n[[Category:Psychedelic rock music groups from California]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Orange County, California]]\n[[Category:Garage rock groups from California]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = The Growlers\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = [[File:The_Growlers_Live_Beach_Goth_Tour.jpg|250px|center|alt=The Growlers playing at Beach Goth 2018]]\n| caption          = The Growlers playing at Beach Goth 2018\n| landscape        = no\n| genre            = [[Surf rock]], [[psychedelic rock]], [[garage rock]]\n| years_active     = 2006\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist| \n*Beach Goth Records and Tapes\n*[[Cult Records]]\n*[[Everloving Records]]\n*[[Burger Records]]\n*[[FatCat Records]]\n*Palmist\n*Ayo Silver\n*Smack Face\n}}  \n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist| \n*[[Julian Casablancas]]\n*[[Kirin J. Callinan]]\n*[[Dan Auerbach]]\n*[[Delicate Steve]]\n*[[Allah-Las]]\n*[[Jonathan Richman]]\n*[[The Grand Elegance]]\n*The Abigails\n*Tomorrow's Tulips\n}}\n| website          = {{URL|thegrowlers.com}}\n| current_members  = Brooks Nielsen<br />Matt Taylor<br />Kyle Straka<br />Brad Bowers<br />Adam Wolcott Smith<br />Richard Gowen\n| past_members     = Brian Stewart<br />Warren Thomas<br />Patrick Palomo<br /> Clark Davison<br /> Miles Patterson<br />Zachary Aguirre<br />Scott Montoya<br />Anthony Braun Perry<br /> Jason Kaiser\n}}\n\n'''The Growlers''' are an American band from Southern California . They began their career in the [[Orange County]] city of [[Dana Point, California]] in 2006. They are currently based in [[Costa Mesa]].<ref name=\"Reynolds\">Reynolds, Wyoming (2018) \"[https://ocweekly.com/the-growlers-hope-beach-goths-la-shift-leads-to-its-salvation/ The Growlers Hope Beach Goth's LA Shift Leads To Its Salvation]\", ''[[OC Weekly]]'', August 1, 2018.</ref> The band is currently composed of singer Brooks Nielsen, lead guitarist Matt Taylor and keyboard player/guitarist Kyle Straka.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.therooster.com/blog/growlers-drinking-whiskey-tripping-out-and-getting-weird-living|title=The Growlers: Drinking whiskey, tripping out and getting weird for a living.|last=|first=|date=January 7, 2013|website=the rooster.com|publisher=|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> They have released seven albums, several EPs and a number of singles. The band's sound has been described as \"a trademark style of music that somehow combines surf, pop, rock and beat\" which has been labeled \"Beach Goth\".<ref name=\"Keller\">Keller, Brandy (2010) \"[http://www.spinner.com/2010/03/14/the-growlers-interview-sxsw-2010/ The Growlers Interview: SXSW 2010]\", spinner.com, March 14, 2010, retrieved January 28, 2012</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nSinger Brooks Nielsen and music director/guitarist Matt Taylor met in high school in the beach town of Dana Point, California, bonding over surfing, skating, and partying.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smashboxstudios.com/hype/growlers-southern-californias-beach-goth-beatles-mania/|title=The Growlers are Southern California\u2019s Beach Goth Beatles, Mania and All|last=Salek|first=Yassi|date=November 4, 2014|website=smashboxstudios.com|publisher=|language=en-GB}}</ref> When offered the chance to perform at a house party, the duo quickly wrote their first six songs in a single day, leading to the first incarnation of the band that would eventually become The Growlers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.laweekly.com/the-growlers-have-a-shot-at-the-big-time-but-it-makes-them-feel-a-bit-uneasy/|title=The Growlers Have a Shot at the Big Time, But it Makes Them Feel a Bit Uneasy|last=Flanders|first=Kai|date=April 19, 2012|website=laweekly.com|publisher=|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\nAfter releasing a handful of self-recorded cassettes and CDs, The Growlers issued their first studio album, ''Are You in or Out?'' in 2009 on Everloving Records. Aquarium Drunkard described it as \u201cconsistent in sound and tone that is as enjoyable straight through or on shuffle\u2026 Taken as a whole, the record is a beautiful mix of late 60\u2019s freak-out, folk calmness and surf rock.\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aquariumdrunkard.com/2009/10/05/the-growlers-are-you-in-or-out/|title=The Growlers :: Are You In Or Out?|last=Kramer|first=B=October 5, 2009|website=aquariumdrunkard.com|publisher=|language=en-GB}}</ref> Their second album, ''Hot Tropics'', was released in 2010, also on Everloving Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thegrowlers.com/about|title=Growlers: About|accessdate=October 31, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111024192555/http://thegrowlers.com/about|archivedate=October 24, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.phoenixnewtimes.com/uponsun/2011/04/qa_the_growlers_brooks_nielsen.php|title=Q&A: The Growlers' Brooks Nielsen Talks Getting Drunk, Being Weird and Bill Murray|work=Phoenix New Times|accessdate=June 4, 2013}}</ref> The band's third album, ''[[Hung at Heart]]'', the first to feature Anthony Braun Perry on bass and Jason Kaiser on percussion, was released in 2013.<ref name=\"everloving.com\">[http://www.everloving.com/site/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=736:hung-at-heart&catid=1&Itemid=100004 Hung At Heart]. Everloving.com (November 8, 2012). Retrieved on December 14, 2013.</ref> The band originally worked with [[Dan Auerbach]] to record the album, but the finished version never saw official release. Instead the band recorded a new version of the album in Costa Mesa, CA with Mike McHugh at his Distillery Recording Studio, to get a more lo-fi sound. \n\n''[[Chinese Fountain]]'', their new \"more grown up, well polished\" album was released September 23, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://greatescapefestival.com/artist-interview-the-growlers/|title=Artist Interview: The Growlers|work=The Great Escape|access-date=March 24, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141108093203/http://greatescapefestival.com/artist-interview-the-growlers/|archive-date=November 8, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> This album was produced by JP Plunier at Seahorse Studios in Los Angeles, CA. While touring the album, the band expanded their live band with percussionist [[Nick Murray (musician)|Nick Murray]]. <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://guide.originalfuzz.com/articles/five-minutes-with-nick-murray|title=5 Minutes With Nick Murray|newspaper=Original Fuzz|access-date=October 11, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610174705/http://guide.originalfuzz.com/articles/five-minutes-with-nick-murray|archivedate=June 10, 2016}}</ref> <ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SNmFGKP3tAo YouTube ~ ''the Growlers (Live on KEXP)'']</ref>\n\nThe band's fifth studio album, ''[[City Club (album)|City Club]]'' was released by [[Cult Records]] on September 30, 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/julian-casablancas/96356|title=Listen to Julian Casablancas-produced new single by The Growlers|last=Earls|first=John|date=September 12, 2016|website=nme.com|publisher=|language=en-GB|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> while they embarked on a supporting tour in the same month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2016/07/cult-records-announces-new-growlers-album-fall-tou.html|title=Cult Records Announces New Growlers Album, Fall Tour|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> It was the first Growlers album to be credited solely to Brooks Nielsen and Matt Taylor, as opposed to the whole band.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.ascap.com/aceclient/AceWeb/#ace/search/workID/891050161|title=ACE Repertory|last=ACE|website=mobile.ascap.com|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> Nielsen and Taylor wrote and recorded demos for the album over a span of 2 to 3 months with the help of Kyle Mullarky at his studio in Topanga Canyon, CA. It was preceded by the title track as a single produced by [[Julian Casablancas]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/08/the-growlers-share-julian-casablancas-produced-single-city-club-listen/|title=The Growlers share Julian Casablancas-produced single \u201cCity Club\u201d \u2014 listen|date=August 26, 2016|language=en-US|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> who also owns the label.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bkmag.com/2016/09/16/brooks-nielsen-on-the-growlers-new-julian-casablancas-produced-album-city-club-cult-records/|title=The Growlers' Brooks Nielsen On New Julian Casablancas-Produced Album|last=Romano|first=Evan|date=September 16, 2016|website=Brooklyn Magazine|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> Neither drummer Scott Montoya nor bass player Anthony Perry feature on the album.<ref>http://www.allmusic.com/album/city-club-mw0002976520/credits</ref> On September 25, the band confirmed Montoya's departure from the band and stated that Perry was set to return in the near future.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/losGrowlers/posts/10153840189555079|title=The GROWLERS - Timeline {{!}} Facebook|website=www.facebook.com|access-date=October 11, 2016}}</ref> The band toured for this album with Brad Bowers on bass, Adam Wolcott Smith on keyboard, and Richard Gowen on drums.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://first-avenue.com/performer/growlers|title=The Growlers: First Avenue|access-date=March 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kcrw.com/people/the-growlers|title=The Growlers: KRCW|access-date=March 13, 2017}}</ref> Whether their membership in the band is permanent is currently unclear.\n\nThe band released ''[[Casual Acquaintances]]'' on July 27, 2018, a collection of demos and unused material from the City Club sessions.  \n\nThe Growlers have toured with artists such as [[The Black Keys]], [[Devendra Banhart]], Julian Casablancas, [[Night Beats]], and [[Jonathan Richman]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dothebay.com/p/interview-the-growlers|title=INTERVIEW + GIVEAWAY: THE GROWLERS|last=Gomez|first=Dominique|date=2016|website=Do The Bay|publisher=|access-date=June 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Cody Peterson |url=http://omahype.com/event/the-night-beats-w-the-growlers-snake-island/ |title=Omahype |publisher=Omahype |date= |accessdate=June 4, 2013}}</ref> They have also appeared at numerous festivals including Coachella, Bonnaroo, Primavera Sound, Lollapalooza, Austin City Limits, Sasquatch!, Wakarusa, Treasure Island, Fun Fun Fun, Bestival, Way Out West, End of The Road, Burgerama III, [[Rock in Rio]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/rock-in-rio/2011/noticia/2011/10/marcelo-camelo-e-growlers-fazem-show-morno-no-palco-sunset.html|title=Marcelo Camelo e The Growlers fazem show morno no Palco Sunset|publisher=G1.globo.com|accessdate=June 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com.br/noticia/marcelo-camelo-e-growlers-no-rock-rio/|title=Marcelo Camelo e The Growlers unem for\u00e7as no Rock in Rio|publisher=Rolling Stone|accessdate=June 4, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425064633/http://www.rollingstone.com.br/noticia/marcelo-camelo-e-growlers-no-rock-rio/|archive-date=April 25, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Outside Lands Music and Arts Festival|Outside Lands]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/2013/08/outside-lands-2013-best-things-day-two-saturday-nine-inch-nails-phoenix/|title=Outside Lands 2013: The 10 Best Things We Saw On Saturday|last=|first=|date=August 11, 2013|website=SPIN|publisher=|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Beach Goth==\n\nThe band has organized their annual Beach Goth festival since 2012. The event typically features performances by bands representing a variety of genres, including [[pop music|pop]], [[rap]], [[hip hop]], [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]], and [[rock music|rock]]. Over the years, the event has included costume contests, amusement park rides, and live performances of [[Rocky Horror Picture Show]]. The Growlers have headlined both Saturday and Sunday night of the annual Beach Goth festival since its inception.\n\nThe likes of [[Die Antwoord]], [[Grimes (musician)|Grimes]], [[Gucci Mane]], [[Julian Casablancas]], [[Mac DeMarco]], [[The Drums]], [[Foxygen]], [[White Arrows]] and [[Ghost B.C.]] have appeared at the festival.\n\nBeach Goth 4 (October 2015) was hosted by [[Pauly Shore]] and featured live performances of [[Rocky Horror Picture Show]] throughout the weekend as well as a performance of [[The Doors]] song \"People Are Strange\" by The Growlers and [[Julian Casablancas]].\n\nThe 2016 edition of Beach Goth took place at The Observatory in Santa Ana, CA on October 23\u201324, 2016.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/10/beach-goth-2016-festival-review-and-gallery/|title=Beach Goth 2016 Festival Review and Gallery|date=October 25, 2016|newspaper=Consequence of Sound|language=en-US|access-date=November 25, 2016}}</ref> It was originally scheduled to take place at the Oak Canyon Park but was moved last minute due to unexplained circumstances. The festival's lineup included [[Bon Iver]], [[TLC (group)|TLC]], [[James Blake (musician)|James Blake]], [[2 Live Crew]], [[Violent Femmes]], [[Future Islands]], [[Reel Big Fish]], [[The Faint]], [[the Pharcyde]], [[Left\u00f6ver Crack]], and [[DJ Quik]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stereogum.com/1887764/beach-goth-2016-lineup/news/|title=Beach Goth 2016 Lineup|date=July 13, 2016|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> While it was hailed a success, the outdoor festival suffered from rain and resultant street flooding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-beach-goth-20161020-snap-story.html|title=Beach Goth's lineup had the goods, but fest may not be ready for its close-up|last=Brown|first=August|website=latimes.com|access-date=November 25, 2016}}</ref> This caused the Growlers to delay their own set due to equipment damage.<ref name=\":0\" /> In the aftermath, the band issued an apology.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDue to an ongoing lawsuit with Noise Group (owners of The Observatory venue) over the Beach Goth trademark,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ocweekly.com/beach-goth-is-dead-the-observatory-suing-the-growlers-only-confirms-it-7660356/|title=Beach Goth is Dead. The Observatory Suing The Growlers Only Confirms It|date=November 15, 2016|work=OC Weekly|access-date=August 17, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> 2017's festival took on the name \"The Growlers Six\", which took place on October 28 & 29 at the LA Waterfront. The festival included artists such as the Yeah Yeah Yeahs, Modest Mouse, and the Butthole Surfers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/08/yeah-yeah-yeahs-modest-mouse-butthole-surfers-to-play-the-growlers-six-festival/|title=Yeah Yeah Yeahs, Modest Mouse, Butthole Surfers to play The Growlers Six Festival|date=August 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Growlers returned to their trademarked \"Beach Goth\" brand name for the 7th annual festival, taking place at the Los Angeles Historic State Park on August 5, 2018. Beach Goth 7 hosted performances by The Growlers, [[Jonathan Richman]], [[The Voidz]], [[The Drums]], [[La Luz (band)|La Luz]], and [[Gwar|GWAR]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://buzzbands.la/2018/08/03/beach-goth-7-here-are-your-set-times-for-sunday/|title=Beach Goth 7: Here are your set times for Sunday \u2013 buzzbands.la|date=August 3, 2018|work=buzzbands.la|access-date=August 17, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|The Growlers discography}}\n\n===Studio Albums===\n*''Are You In or Out?'' (2009), Everloving Records\n*''Hot Tropics'' (2010), Everloving Records\n*''[[Hung at Heart]]'' (2013), Everloving Records (US), FatCat Records (UK & Europe), Smack Face Records (Australia & New Zealand)\n*''[[Chinese Fountain]]'' (2014), Everloving Records (US), FatCat Records (UK & Europe), Smack Face Records (Australia & New Zealand)\n*[[City Club (album)|''City Club'']] (2016), Cult Records (US/EU)\n*''Natural Affair'' (2019), Beach Goth Records & Tapes\n\n===EPs===\n*''Split Growlers/Thee Ludds'' (2011), Palmist, limited to 500 copies<ref>[http://www.palmistrecords.com/?p=851 GROWLERS/ THEE LUDDS SPLIT 12\u2033 OUT TODAY IN UK/ EUROPE | Palmist]. Palmistrecords.com (October 3, 2011). Retrieved on December 14, 2013.</ref>\n*''Gay Thoughts/Uncle Sam's a Dick'' (2013), Ayo Silver<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ayosilver.bigcartel.com/product/the-growlers-gay-thoughts-uncle-sam-s-a-dick|title=Ayo Silver!|work=bigcartel.com}}</ref>\n*''Gilded Pleasures''  (2013), Everloving Records (US), Smack Face Records (Australia & New Zealand)\n*''Lonely This Christmas'' (2017), Beach Goth Records & Tapes\n\n===Other Releases===\n*''Greatest Hits'' (2007), self-released\n*[[Casual Acquaintances (The Growlers album)|''Casual Acquaintances'']] (2018) Beach Goth Records & Tapes (US)\n\n===Singles===\n*\"Gay Thoughts\" / \"Feeling Good\" (2011), Everloving, limited to 1000 copies on 7\" vinyl<ref>[http://www.everloving.com/site/index.php?option=com_wrapper&view=wrapper&Itemid=100086 Vinyl Shop]. Everloving.com. Retrieved on December 14, 2013.</ref>\n*\"Uncle Sam's a Dick\" / \"Drinking Song for Kids\" (2012), no label, limited to 500 copies, of which 250 each were sold online and at concerts on 7\" vinyl<ref>{{cite web|url=http://store.cinderblock.com/uncle-sam-s-a-dick-7-vinyl.html|title=Uncle Sam's a dick (7\")|website=cinderblock|accessdate=January 14, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026024625/http://store.cinderblock.com/uncle-sam-s-a-dick-7-vinyl.html|archivedate=October 26, 2012}}</ref>\n*\"Late Bloomers\" (2017), Cult Records LLC\n*\"Monotonia\" (2017), Beach Goth Records & Tapes\n*\"California\" (2017), Beach Goth Records & Tapes\n*\u201dWho Loves The Scum?\u201d (2018), Beach Goth Records  & Tapes\n*\"Natural Affair\" (2019), Beach Goth Records & Tapes\n*\"Foghorn Town\" (2019), Beach Goth Records & Tapes\n*\"Try Hard Fool\" (2019), Beach Goth Records & Tapes\n*\"Pulp Of Youth\" (2019), Beach Goth Records & Tapes\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://thegrowlers.com/}}\n\n{{The Growlers}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Growlers, The}}\n[[Category:Psychedelic rock music groups from California]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Orange County, California]]\n[[Category:Garage rock groups from California]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in California]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toOrange County(link changed toOrange County, California) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Growlers"}
{"title_page": "Donald P. Wagner", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=December 2010}}\n{{Infobox state representative\n|name           = Don Wagner\n|image          = Donald_Wagner_Official_City_Portrait.jpg\n|alt            = \n|office         = Member of the<br />[[Orange County Board of Supervisors]]<br />from the 3rd District\n|term_start     = March 27, 2019\n|term_end       = \n|predecessor    = [[Todd Spitzer]]\n|successor      = \n|office1        = [[Mayor]] of [[Irvine, California]]\n|term_start1    = December 13, 2016\n|term_end1      = March 26, 2019\n|predecessor1   = [[Steven Choi]]\n|successor1     = [[Christina L. Shea]]\n|state_assembly2= California\n|district2      = [[California's 68th State Assembly district|68th]]\n|term_start2    = December 6, 2010\n|term_end2      = November 30, 2016\n|predecessor2   = [[Chuck DeVore]]\n|successor2     = [[Steven Choi]]\n|prior_term2    = [[California's 70th State Assembly district|70th]] district (2010\u20132012)\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1960|12|3}}\n|birth_place    = [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|nationality    = American\n|party          = [[California Republican Party|Republican]]\n|residence      = [[Irvine, California]]\n|alma_mater     = [[University of California, Los Angeles]]<br />[[University of California, Hastings College of the Law]]\n|occupation     = [[Attorney at law|Attorney]]\n|profession     = \n|signature      = \n|website        = [https://web.archive.org/web/20110726133913/http://arc.asm.ca.gov/member/70/ Donald P. Wagner]\n|footnotes      = \n}}\n\n'''Donald P. \"Don\" Wagner''' (born December 3, 1960) is an American politician, currently serving as a member of the [[Orange County Board of Supervisors]] for the 3rd district. He previously served as mayor of [[Irvine, California]] and as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] member of the [[California State Assembly]], representing the [[California's 68th State Assembly district|68th district]], which includes portions of [[Orange County, California|Orange County]].\n\n==Education and family==\nWagner received a bachelor's degree in English from the [[University of California, Los Angeles]], and a Juris Doctorate in 1987 from the [[University of California, Hastings College of the Law]] and was admitted to the California Bar in the same year.<ref name=\"Project Vote Smart Biography\">[http://www.votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=29636 Project Vote Smart Biography]</ref>\n\nWagner is married to [[Superior Courts of California|Superior Court Judge]] Megan Wagner, and he and his family resides in Irvine, California.\n\n==Legal and political career==\nWagner was an attorney for Kindel and Anderson from 1987 to 1993, and for Wagner and Associates from 1993 to 1998. He has been an attorney for Wagner Lautsch Limited Liability Partnership since 1998.<ref name=\"Project Vote Smart Biography\"/>\n\nWagner served on several committees or advisory boards for the Orange County Bar Association and as a Judge Pro Tempore in the Superior Court of Orange County. Other previous positions include three active terms as a member of the South Orange County Community College District Board of Trustees. He founded and served as the first president of the Orange County Chapter of the [[Federalist Society]].\n\nIn 2013, he sought election to the [[California State Senate]] to succeed [[Mimi Walters]], who was elected to the [[United States House of Representatives]] the prior year.  He lost the special election to [[Orange County, California|Orange County]] Supervisor [[John Moorlach]]\n\nHe won the [[2016 Irvine mayoral election]], and won reelection in the [[2018 Irvine mayoral election]].\n\n==California State Assemblyman==\n[[File:Lake forest coffee2.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Assemblyman Wagner speaking at a town coffee meet at Lake Forest, CA.]]\nIn 2010, Wagner narrowly won the Republican [[primary election]] for the 70th Assembly District over Irvine City Councilman [[Steven Choi]].<ref>[http://elections.cdn.sos.ca.gov/sov/2010-primary/pdf/2010-complete-sov.pdf]</ref> He then won the [[general election]] with 58.2% of the votes.<ref>[http://www.sacbee.com/2010/11/01/3150569/california-assembly-results.html Sacramento Bee, California Assembly General election results] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101106052529/http://www.sacbee.com/2010/11/01/3150569/california-assembly-results.html |date=November 6, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nFor the 2011\u20132012 legislative session, Wagner was appointed to these committees:\n* Aging and Long-Term Care Committee\n* Appropriations Committee\n* Budget Committee\n* Education Committee\n* Judiciary Committee \u2013 Vice Chair\n\n===2014 California State Assembly ===\n{{see also|California State Assembly elections, 2014}}\n{{Election box open primary begin no change\n| title = [[California's 68th State Assembly district]] election, 2014\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Republican Party\n| candidate = Donald P. Wagner ([[incumbent]])\n| votes = 35,223\n| percentage = 69.7\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Democratic Party\n| candidate = Anne Cameron\n| votes = 15,297\n| percentage = 30.3\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 50,520\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box open primary general election no change}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Republican Party\n| candidate = Donald P. Wagner ([[incumbent]])\n| votes = 66,445\n| percentage = 68.4\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Democratic Party\n| candidate = Anne Cameron\n| votes = 30,749\n| percentage = 31.6\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 97,194\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no change\n| winner = California Republican Party\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Political ratings==\n* [[Project Vote Smart]] provides the following results from legislative scorecards.<ref name=\"Project Vote Smart\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.votesmart.org/issue_rating_category.php?can_id=29636\n  |title=Assembly Member Donald P Wagner (CA)\n  |work=vote-smart.org\n  |publisher=[[Project Vote Smart]]\n  |accessdate=2011-07-26\n  }}</ref>\n* [[National Rifle Association]] \u2013 A in 2010{{citation needed|date=July 2012}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.facebook.com/DonWagnerCA/ Wagner's Facebook profile]\n* [http://www.votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=29636 Project Vote Smart Biography]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wagner, Donald}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Hastings College of the Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the California State Assembly]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Irvine, California]]\n[[Category:Orange County Supervisors]]\n[[Category:People from Irvine, California]]\n[[Category:California state court judges]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Federalist Society members]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=December 2010}}\n{{Infobox state representative\n|name           = Don Wagner\n|image          = Donald_Wagner_Official_City_Portrait.jpg\n|alt            = \n|office         = Member of the<br />[[Orange County Board of Supervisors]]<br />from the 3rd District\n|term_start     = March 27, 2019\n|term_end       = \n|predecessor    = [[Todd Spitzer]]\n|successor      = \n|office1        = [[Mayor]] of [[Irvine, California]]\n|term_start1    = December 13, 2016\n|term_end1      = March 26, 2019\n|predecessor1   = [[Steven Choi]]\n|successor1     = [[Christina L. Shea]]\n|state_assembly2= California\n|district2      = [[California's 68th State Assembly district|68th]]\n|term_start2    = December 6, 2010\n|term_end2      = November 30, 2016\n|predecessor2   = [[Chuck DeVore]]\n|successor2     = [[Steven Choi]]\n|prior_term2    = [[California's 70th State Assembly district|70th]] district (2010\u20132012)\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1960|12|3}}\n|birth_place    = [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|nationality    = American\n|party          = [[California Republican Party|Republican]]\n|residence      = [[Irvine, California]]\n|alma_mater     = [[University of California, Los Angeles]]<br />[[University of California, Hastings College of the Law]]\n|occupation     = [[Attorney at law|Attorney]]\n|profession     = \n|signature      = \n|website        = [https://web.archive.org/web/20110726133913/http://arc.asm.ca.gov/member/70/ Donald P. Wagner]\n|footnotes      = \n}}\n\n'''Donald P. \"Don\" Wagner''' (born December 3, 1960) is an American politician, currently serving as a member of the [[Orange County Board of Supervisors]] for the 3rd district. He previously served as mayor of [[Irvine, California]] and as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] member of the [[California State Assembly]], representing the [[California's 68th State Assembly district|68th district]], which includes portions of [[Orange County, California|Orange County]].\n\n==Education and family==\nWagner received a bachelor's degree in English from the [[University of California, Los Angeles]], and a Juris Doctorate in 1987 from the [[University of California, Hastings College of the Law]] and was admitted to the California Bar in the same year.<ref name=\"Project Vote Smart Biography\">[http://www.votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=29636 Project Vote Smart Biography]</ref>\n\nWagner is married to [[Superior Courts of California|Superior Court Judge]] Megan Wagner, and he and his family resides in Irvine, California.\n\n==Legal and political career==\nWagner was an attorney for Kindel and Anderson from 1987 to 1993, and for Wagner and Associates from 1993 to 1998. He has been an attorney for Wagner Lautsch Limited Liability Partnership since 1998.<ref name=\"Project Vote Smart Biography\"/>\n\nWagner served on several committees or advisory boards for the Orange County Bar Association and as a Judge Pro Tempore in the Superior Court of Orange County. Other previous positions include three active terms as a member of the South Orange County Community College District Board of Trustees. He founded and served as the first president of the Orange County Chapter of the [[Federalist Society]].\n\nIn 2013, he sought election to the [[California State Senate]] to succeed [[Mimi Walters]], who was elected to the [[United States House of Representatives]] the prior year.  He lost the special election to [[Orange County]] Supervisor [[John Moorlach]]\n\nHe won the [[2016 Irvine mayoral election]], and won reelection in the [[2018 Irvine mayoral election]].\n\n==California State Assemblyman==\n[[File:Lake forest coffee2.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Assemblyman Wagner speaking at a town coffee meet at Lake Forest, CA.]]\nIn 2010, Wagner narrowly won the Republican [[primary election]] for the 70th Assembly District over Irvine City Councilman [[Steven Choi]].<ref>[http://elections.cdn.sos.ca.gov/sov/2010-primary/pdf/2010-complete-sov.pdf]</ref> He then won the [[general election]] with 58.2% of the votes.<ref>[http://www.sacbee.com/2010/11/01/3150569/california-assembly-results.html Sacramento Bee, California Assembly General election results] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101106052529/http://www.sacbee.com/2010/11/01/3150569/california-assembly-results.html |date=November 6, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nFor the 2011\u20132012 legislative session, Wagner was appointed to these committees:\n* Aging and Long-Term Care Committee\n* Appropriations Committee\n* Budget Committee\n* Education Committee\n* Judiciary Committee \u2013 Vice Chair\n\n===2014 California State Assembly ===\n{{see also|California State Assembly elections, 2014}}\n{{Electio